.TH "WHOHOLDS" "1" "2026\-04\-12" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
whoholds \- find which processes are holding a file lock or binding a
network port
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]whoholds\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]target\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Shows the process name, PID, and owner for every process holding a file
lock or binding a network port.
Useful for diagnosing \(lqfile is locked\(rq or \(lqport is already in
use\(rq errors.
.PP
\f[I]target\f[R] is either a file path or a port specifier.
\f[B]whoholds\f[R] auto\-detects which you mean:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]File path\f[R] \(em any argument containing a path separator, or an
argument that names an existing file on disk.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]:port\f[R] \(em a leading \f[B]:\f[R] is unambiguous: \f[B]whoholds
:8080\f[R] always queries port 8080.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Bare number\f[R] \(em treated as a port only if a file with that
name does not exist on disk.
.PP
Without elevation, only processes belonging to the current user are
visible.
A warning is printed to stderr when not running as administrator.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(enpid\-only\f[R]
Output only PIDs, one per line.
Suitable for piping to \f[B]wargs\f[R] or \f[B]kill\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enfull\-path\f[R], \f[B]\-l\f[R]
Show the full executable path instead of just the process name.
Requires elevation for system processes.
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Output results as a JSON object.
Each process entry includes \f[B]pid\f[R], \f[B]name\f[R],
\f[B]path\f[R], \f[B]state\f[R], and \f[B]resource\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(endescribe\f[R]
Output structured tool metadata as JSON (flags, examples, composability)
and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R]
Force coloured output, overriding \f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version and exit.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success \(em query completed (even if no holders were found).
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Target not found or query error.
.TP
\f[B]125\f[R]
Usage error (bad arguments).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables coloured output (no\-color.org).
.SH ELEVATION
\f[B]whoholds\f[R] always prints a warning to stderr when not running as
administrator.
Without elevation, the Restart Manager API (Windows) and \f[B]lsof\f[R]
(Linux/macOS) may only see processes belonging to the current user.
A file held by a system service or another user\(cqs process will not
appear in results.
.PP
When elevated, file lock detection and port binding detection cover all
processes, and \f[B]\(enfull\-path\f[R] returns paths for system
processes.
.SH PLATFORM NOTES
On Windows, file locks are detected via the Win32 Restart Manager API.
Port bindings are detected via the IP Helper
\f[B]GetExtendedTcpTable\f[R] / \f[B]GetExtendedUdpTable\f[R] APIs (TCP
+ UDP, IPv4 + IPv6).
.PP
On Linux and macOS, \f[B]whoholds\f[R] delegates to \f[B]lsof\f[R],
which must be installed.
\f[B]lsof\f[R] is present by default on most distributions and macOS.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
whoholds myapp.dll

whoholds :8080

whoholds 8080

whoholds myapp.dll \-\-pid\-only

whoholds myapp.dll \-\-pid\-only | wargs kill \-f {}

whoholds :8080 \-\-json

whoholds \-\-describe
.EE
